{{Infobox Hieroglyphen Zweispaltig
|NAME-ERWEITERT = {{ill|New Kingdom of Egypt|de|Neues Reich}}
|NAME = <hiero>S29-Aa17-V28-D61-N14:N35</hiero><br/>Seba-en-Sah<br /> ''Sb3-n-S3ḥ'' <br/> ''Star of the Descending One (Toe or Foot Star)'' 
|BILD1 = Orion-Sternkarte.png 
|BILD1-BREITE = 250px
|BILD1-BESCHREIBUNG = Constellation "Sah" (Orion)
}}

'''Seba-en-Sah''' (also '''Tepi-a Sah'''; ''First of the Descending One'') is the {{ill|Ancient Egypt|de|Altes Ägypten}} name for {{ill|Rigel|de|Rigel (Stern)}} ({{ill|Beta Orionis|de|β Orionis}}), the principal star of the {{ill|Sah (constellation)|de|Sah (Sternbild)}} constellation in ancient Egyptian astronomy. 

## Mythological Connections
Seba-en-Sah served as the namesake for the Sah constellation and as a dekan star depicted on the astronomical ceiling of {{ill|Senenmut|de|Senenmut}}’s tomb and in the {{ill|day selection calendar|de|Tagewählkalender (Altes Ägypten)}}. In the {{ill|Ramesside star clocks|de|Ramessidische Sternuhren}}, Seba-en-Sah represented the beginning of the {{ill|Fifth Hour of the Night|de|Fünfte Nachtstunde (Altes Ägypten)}} on {{ill|1 Achet IV|de|Achet#Datierungen}}.<ref name=L135>Christian Leitz: ''Altägyptische Sternuhren''. p.&nbsp;135.</ref> {{ill|Rolf Krauss|de|Rolf Krauss (Ägyptologe)}} rejected the identification of Seba-en-Sah with Rigel based on his findings about the {{ill|Sothic cycle|de|Sothis-Zyklus}}. He argued that the initial reference point for the heliacal rise of Sirius was {{ill|Elephantine|de|Elephantine}}, excluding the possibility of identifying Seba-en-Sah with Rigel:

{{Zitat|Krauss must assert this,… otherwise his entire calculations would collapse… The means involve a distorted and substantially incomplete representation of alternative arguments.|Christian Leitz, ''Altägyptische Sternuhren''<ref name=L135/>}}
[[File:Senenmut-Grab.JPG|thumb|The astronomical ceiling in the tomb of Senenmut]]
In the Ramesside star clocks, the {{ill|midnight|de|Mitternacht}} {{ill|culmination (astronomy)|de|Kulmination (Astronomie)}} of Seba-en-Sah is recorded for {{ill|23 and 24 Achet III|de|Achet#Datierungen}}.<ref>14 and 15 November {{ill|Julian calendar|de|Julianischer Kalender}} in 1463 BCE.</ref> This culmination occurred during the middle of the {{ill|Seventh Hour of the Night|de|Siebte Nachtstunde (Altes Ägypten)}}. Remarkably, this date aligns precisely with the details found on the astronomical ceiling of the {{ill|Tomb TT353|de|TT353}} (Senenmut’s tomb), suggesting the astronomical arrangements were drawn up in 1463 BCE. It is therefore no coincidence that the astronomical ceiling in Senenmut’s tomb served as a template for dekan arrangements, which continued to be copied during the Ramesside period.<ref name=L136/>

Another piece of evidence supporting the copying of such ceilings in later periods is the absence of the {{ill|planet}} {{ill|Mars|de|Mars (Planet)}}, even though Mars appears in other texts.<ref name=L136>Christian Leitz: ''Altägyptische Sternuhren''. p.&nbsp;136.</ref>

