In the Ramesside star clocks, the {{ill|midnight|de|Mitternacht|qq=draft}} {{ill|culmination|de|Kulmination (Astronomie)|qq=draft}} of Seba-en-Sah is recorded for {{ill|23 and 24 Achet III|de|Achet#Datierungen|1=Season_of_the_Inundation#Months|lt=Achet|qq=draft}}.<ref>14 and 15 November {{ill|Julian calendar|1=Julian calendar|2=ja|3=ユリウス暦|4=zh|5=儒略曆|6=ru|7=Юлианский_календарь|8=de|9=Julianischer_Kalender|10=es|11=Calendario juliano|de|Julianischer Kalender|qq=draft}} in 1463 BCE.</ref> This culmination occurred during the middle of the {{ill|Seventh Hour of the Night|de|Siebte Nachtstunde (Altes Ägypten)|qq=draft}}. Remarkably, this date aligns precisely with the details found on the astronomical ceiling of the {{ill|Tomb TT353|de|TT353|qq=draft}} (Senenmut’s tomb), suggesting the astronomical arrangements were drawn up in 1463 BCE. It is therefore no coincidence that the astronomical ceiling in Senenmut’s tomb served as a template for dekan arrangements, which continued to be copied during the Ramesside period.<ref name=L136/>

Another piece of evidence supporting the copying of such ceilings in later periods is the absence of the [[:en:Planet|planet]] {{ill|Mars|de|Mars (Planet)|qq=draft}}, even though Mars appears in other texts.<ref name=L136>Christian Leitz: ''Altägyptische Sternuhren''. p.&nbsp;136.</ref>

