'''Seba-en-Sah''' (also '''Tepi-a Sah'''; ''First of the Descending One'') is the {{ill|Ancient Egypt|de|Altes Ägypten|qq=draft}} name for {{ill|Rigel|de|Rigel (Stern)|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Beta Orionis|de|β Orionis|qq=draft}}), the principal star of the {{ill|Sah (constellation)|de|Sah (Sternbild)|qq=draft|lt=Sah}} constellation in ancient Egyptian astronomy. 

== Mythological Connections ==
Seba-en-Sah served as the namesake for the Sah constellation and as a dekan star depicted on the astronomical ceiling of {{ill|Senenmut|de|Senenmut|qq=draft}}’s tomb and in the {{ill|day selection calendar|de|Tagewählkalender (Altes Ägypten)|qq=draft}}. In the {{ill|Ramesside star clocks|de|Ramessidische Sternuhren|qq=draft}}, Seba-en-Sah represented the beginning of the {{ill|Fifth Hour of the Night|de|Fünfte Nachtstunde (Altes Ägypten)|qq=draft}} on {{ill|1 Achet IV|de|Achet#Datierungen|1=Season_of_the_Inundation#Months|lt=Achet|qq=draft}}.<ref name=L135>Christian Leitz: ''Altägyptische Sternuhren''. p.&nbsp;135.</ref> {{ill|Rolf Krauss|de|Rolf Krauss (Ägyptologe)|qq=draft}} rejected the identification of Seba-en-Sah with Rigel based on his findings about the {{ill|Sothic cycle|de|Sothis-Zyklus|qq=draft}}. He argued that the initial reference point for the heliacal rise of Sirius was {{ill|Elephantine|de|Elephantine|qq=draft}}, excluding the possibility of identifying Seba-en-Sah with Rigel:

{{Zitat|Krauss must assert this,… otherwise his entire calculations would collapse… The means involve a distorted and substantially incomplete representation of alternative arguments.|Christian Leitz, ''Altägyptische Sternuhren''<ref name=L135/>}}
[[File:Senenmut-Grab.JPG|thumb|The astronomical ceiling in the tomb of Senenmut]]
In the Ramesside star clocks, the {{ill|midnight|de|Mitternacht|qq=draft}} {{ill|culmination|de|Kulmination (Astronomie)|qq=draft}} of Seba-en-Sah is recorded for {{ill|23 and 24 Achet III|de|Achet#Datierungen|1=Season_of_the_Inundation#Months|lt=Achet|qq=draft}}.<ref>14 and 15 November {{ill|Julian calendar|1=Julian calendar|2=ja|3=ユリウス暦|4=zh|5=儒略曆|6=ru|7=Юлианский_календарь|8=de|9=Julianischer_Kalender|10=es|11=Calendario juliano|de|Julianischer Kalender|qq=draft}} in 1463 BCE.</ref> This culmination occurred during the middle of the {{ill|Seventh Hour of the Night|de|Siebte Nachtstunde (Altes Ägypten)|qq=draft}}. Remarkably, this date aligns precisely with the details found on the astronomical ceiling of the {{ill|Tomb TT353|de|TT353|qq=draft}} (Senenmut’s tomb), suggesting the astronomical arrangements were drawn up in 1463 BCE. It is therefore no coincidence that the astronomical ceiling in Senenmut’s tomb served as a template for dekan arrangements, which continued to be copied during the Ramesside period.<ref name=L136/>

Another piece of evidence supporting the copying of such ceilings in later periods is the absence of the [[:en:Planet|planet]] {{ill|Mars|de|Mars (Planet)|qq=draft}}, even though Mars appears in other texts.<ref name=L136>Christian Leitz: ''Altägyptische Sternuhren''. p.&nbsp;136.</ref>

